As shown in Fig. 8(A), different concentrations of Co2+ (0 ∼ 330 μM) were added to the working solution. The experimental results show that with the increasing of Co2+ concentration in G-CQDs solution, the fluorescence intensity of the system decreases continuously. As shown in Fig. 8(D), linear regression analysis was used to fit the curve, with the Co2+ concentration as the abscissa and the fluorescence intensity of G-CQDs as the ordinate. It can be seen that the Co2+ concentration has a good linear relationship with the fluorescence intensity in the range of 0 ∼ 250 μM, Y = − 0.0022X + 0.9404 (R
                        2 = 0.9625), and LOD of G-CQDs to Co2+ was 0.95 μM. Comparison with previous studies on the detection range and LOD of Co2+ (Table 2
                        ) suggests that Co2+ responds well to G-CQDs.
